05546nam a22006255i 9780822386179DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20042004ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223861797 a10.1515/97808223861792doi  a(DE-B1597)553680  a(OCoLC)1229161552  a(OCoLC)1144281549  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aF3429.3.Q6 7aHIS0330002bisacsh04a985/.004983232221 aSalomon, Frank L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Cord Keepers :bKhipus and Cultural Life in a Peruvian Village /cFrank L. Salomon; Sonia Saldívar-Hull, Irene Silverblatt, Walter D. Mignolo. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2004] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (362 p.) :b55 photos (incl. 16 in color), 12 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLatin America otherwise : languages, empires, nations00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tList of Illustrations and Maps -- tList of Tables -- tAbout the Series -- tPreface -- tThe Unread Legacy: An Introduction to Tupicocha's Khipu Problem, and Anthropology's -- t1 Universes of the Legible and Theories of Writing -- t2 A Flowery Script: The Social and Documentary Order of Modern Tupicocha Village -- t3 Living by the ''Book of the Thousand'': Community, Ayllu, and Customary Governance -- t4 The Tupicochan Staff Code -- t5 The Khipu Art after the Inkas -- t6 The Patrimonial Quipocamayos of Tupicocha -- t7 Ayllu Cords and Ayllu Books -- t8 The Half-Life and Afterlife of an Andean Medium: How Modern Villagers Interpret Quipocamayos -- t9 Toward Synthetic Interpretation -- tConclusions -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNone of the world's "lost writings" have proven more perplexing than the mysterious script in which the Inka Empire kept its records. Ancient Andean peoples encoded knowledge in knotted cords of cotton or wool called khipus. In The Cord Keepers, the distinguished anthropologist Frank Salomon breaks new ground with a close ethnography of one Andean village where villagers, surprisingly, have conserved a set of these enigmatic cords to the present day. The "quipocamayos," as the villagers call them, form a sacred patrimony. Keying his reading to the internal life of the ancient kin groups that own the khipus, Salomon suggests that the multicolored cords, with their knots and lavishly woven ornaments, did not mimic speech as most systems of writing do, but instead were anchored in nonverbal codes. The Cord Keepers makes a compelling argument for a close intrinsic link between rituals and visual-sign systems. It indicates that, while Andean graphic representation may differ radically from familiar ideas of writing, it may not lie beyond the reach of scholarly interpretation.In 1994, Salomon witnessed the use of khipus as civic regalia on the heights of Tupicocha, in Peru's central Huarochirí region. By observing the rich ritual surrounding them, studying the village's written records from past centuries, and analyzing the khipus themselves, Salomon opens a fresh chapter in the quest for khipu decipherment. He draws on a decade's field research, early colonial records, and radiocarbon and fiber analysis. Challenging the prevailing idea that the use of khipus ended under early Spanish colonial rule, Salomon reveals that these beautiful objects served, apparently as late as the early twentieth century, to document households' contribution to their kin groups and these kin groups' contribution to their village. The Cord Keepers is a major contribution to Andean history and, more broadly, to understandings of writing and literacy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aQuechua IndianszPeruzHuarochirí (Province)xHisto